<TITLE> Stocks fall, led by banks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 23 (bdnews24.com) -- Stocks closed lower Sunday, influenced by a continued fall in the share prices of banks. Meanwhile, in a trend market observers termed "alarming", Z category shares continued to rise from the previous day's trade. "The prices of these shares are continuously advancing, which is harmful to the market," Yaweer Sayeed, managing director of AIMS of Bangladesh, told bdnews24.com. Sayeed suggested the trend indicated a possible manipulation of the market, which could have fallout, adding the regulator might consider liquidating or de-listing such companies. Chief executive of the Dhaka Stock Exchange Salahuddin Ahmed echoed the concerns, although he said existing securities laws were not strong enough to take punitive steps against the companies. "Our laws need to be amended so that proper action can be taken against these companies to prevent such market manipulation," Salahuddin told bdnews24.com. The DSE's general index rose sharply at the opening bell to touch 3050 points in the first hour of trade, although the market suffered a sustained slump from midday trade to close lower. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed down 27.72 points, or 0.91 percent, to end on 2997.75. The DSI or all share price index finished at 2531.27, down 23.45 points, or 0.91 percent. The bourse's blue chip DSE-20 fell 4.70 points, or 0.20 percent, to end on 2263.57. Turnover on the country's prime bourse totalled Tk 3.16 billion, from 26,983,278 traded shares. Losers beat gainers 149 to 111, with two issues remaining unchanged. The day saw the prices of pharmaceuticals and power companies advancing, while mutual funds closed mixed and banks continued their decline from the previous week. Square Pharma topped the turnover board; rising 0.56 percent to close at Tk 3891. Beximco Pharama followed; ending on Tk 79.80, up 5.27 percent. DESCO rose 12.76 percent to end on 1057.50, while Power Grid Company of Bangladesh finished at Tk 664.50, up 2.03 percent. AB Bank continued its decline, ending 1.75 percent down to close at Tk 3126.25. Among other scrips on the turnover board: Grameen Mutual Fund One, Apex Adelchi Footwear and Summit Power advanced. ICB 1st NRB Mutual Fund and Lafarge Surma Cement lost. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also finished lower. The CSCX or selective categories index fell 16.52 points, or 0.32 percent, to end on 5015.21. The CASPI or all share price index finished at 7817.93, down 29.46 points, or 0.37 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip slumped 44.65 points, or 0.65 percent, to close at 6754.13. Turnover on the port city's bourse totalled Tk 563.79 million. Of the issues traded, 79 advanced, 77 lost and three held steady. bdn
